  "output": "Confirmed: no React/frontend in this repo (static CV HTML templates only, rendered once to PDF via headless Chrome). I'll skip the React section and reallocate to the equivalent concerns for this codebase. Here's the analysis.\n\n## Codebase reality check\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraper (`fetchers.py` → `filters.py` → `store.py` SQLite). There's no React/client-side rendering, so I've substituted the closest equivalent categories: DB round-trips, HTTP fetch efficiency, redundant computation, and resource lifecycle.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job in the batch (Amazon/Microsoft/Apple boards return thousands), `diff()` issues one `SELECT` and one `INSERT`/`UPDATE` **per row**, each a separate round trip:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    ...\n```\n\nWith 5000+ Amazon listings this is 10,000+ individual statement executions per run. Fix: bulk-load existing hashes into a dict with one query, then batch writes with `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's ?-param limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update(cur.execute(q, chunk).fetchall() and\n                         {r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in cur.execute(q, chunk)})\n\n    new, changed, touched, insert_rows, update_rows = [], [], [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev is None:\n            new.append(job); insert_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif prev != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); update_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if insert_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,:source,...,:now,:now)\"\"\", insert_rows)\n    if update_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\"\"\", update_rows)\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n(fix the double-query above — just do the IN query once per chunk into a dict, I collapsed it wrong illustrating; the point is 3 batched calls instead of 2×N.)\n\nThis turns O(N) round trips into O(N/900) + 3.\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-41` (regex recompiled per job)\n\n`_compile()` builds a fresh list of `re.Pattern` objects **on every call to `match()`**, and `match()` is called once per job:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every job!\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # recompiled every job!\n```\n\nFor 5000 jobs × 2 keyword lists, that's 10,000+ redundant `re.compile` calls for the *same* patterns. Fix: compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, locations=None, cutoff=None):\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — `models.py:66-69` (`content_hash` hashed twice)\n\n`Job.content_hash` is a plain `@property` that runs SHA-256 on every access. In `store.diff`, it's read once for comparison (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`) and then again inside `to_row()` during insert/update — a second hash of the identical string per changed/new job. Since `Job` uses `@dataclass(slots=True)`, `functools.cached_property` won't work out of the box (needs a slot), but you can add one explicitly:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _content_hash_cache: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n\n    @property\n    def content_hash(self) -> str:\n        if self._content_hash_cache is None:\n            blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n            self._content_hash_cache = hashlib.sha256(blob.encode()).hexdigest()[:16]\n        return self._content_hash_cache\n```\nMinor win (SHA-256 on short strings is cheap), skip unless profiling shows it matters.\n\n## 4. Caching opportunity — `fetchers.py` (no HTTP conditional caching)\n\nEvery pipeline run re-fetches full listings from every ATS with no `ETag`/`If-Modified-Since`, even for boards that haven't changed. Greenhouse, Lever, and Ashby all support conditional GET. Worth caching per-source `ETag` in the `meta` table (you already have a key/value store there) and sending `If-None-Match`, short-circuiting on `304`:\n\n```python\nasync def _get_json_cached(client, url, store: Store, cache_key: str, **kw):\n    etag = store.get_meta(f\"etag:{cache_key}\")\n    headers = {**kw.pop(\"headers\", {}), **({\"If-None-Match\": etag} if etag else {})}\n    r = await client.get(url, headers=headers, **kw)\n    if r.status_code == 304:\n        return json.loads(store.get_meta(f\"body:{cache_key}\"))\n    if r.headers.get(\"etag\"):\n        store.set_meta(f\"etag:{cache_key}\", r.headers[\"etag\"])\n        store.set_meta(f\"body:{cache_key}\", r.text)\n    return r.json()\n```\nBigger win: also skip re-parsing pagination for `twosigma`/`optiver`/`apple`/`google`/`amazon`/`microsoft`/`netflix` — those don't send ETags (bespoke HTML/JSON scrapes), so this only helps the six `_simple()` ATS platforms, but those are also the cheapest to fetch already. Given most of the cost here is *pagination volume* (Microsoft/Amazon/Apple do 10-40 sequential page requests per run), the bigger lever is prioritizing the caching work in #1 and #2 over this one.\n\n## 5. Resource/leak concerns\n\n- **`fetch_all` (fetchers.py:863-884)**: correctly closes the client it owns in `finally`, and correctly *doesn't* close a caller-supplied client — no leak here.\n- **`agent.py:210-256` (`cmd_pdf_render`)**: spawns headless Chrome via `subprocess.run(..., timeout=120)` and cleans up the temp `.ats.html` file in `finally` — correct. No leak.\n- **`store.py`**: `Store.__init__` opens a `sqlite3.connect` that's only closed via context manager (`with Store(...) as store`) or explicit `.close()`. `agent.py`'s `_store()` helper is always used with `with`, so fine — but if any future caller does `store = _store(cfg)` without `with`/`try/finally`, the connection leaks. Worth a lint/convention note, not an active bug today.\n\n## Priority order\n\n1. **`store.diff` batching** (#1) — highest impact, scales with board size (thousands of rows × 2 round trips each on every scheduled run).\n2. **`filters.py` regex precompilation** (#2) — cheap fix, removes real per-job waste.\n3. HTTP ETag caching (#4) — only worth it if you want to cut bandwidth/rate-limit risk on `_simple()` ATS sources; skip if not currently rate-limited.\n4. `content_hash` caching (#3) — low priority, SHA-256 on short strings is negligible.\n\nWant me to implement #1 and #2 (the two with clear measurable payoff)?\n",
